>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>What is Market Cap?</h1>
      <p>Understanding Market Capitalization: Large, Mid, and Small Cap Stocks Explained.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="intro-section">
      <p>Market capitalization, or "market cap," is one of the most fundamental concepts in investing. It represents the total dollar market value of a company's outstanding shares of stock. By calculating the market cap, investors can quickly determine a company's size, evaluate its level of risk, and compare it to its peers.</p>
      <p>As you build your vocabulary through our <a href="/investing-glossary">Investing Glossary</a>, you'll find that market cap is the primary way the financial industry categorizes companies. Whether you are buying individual stocks or diversified <a href="/what-is-etf">Exchange Traded Funds (ETFs)</a>, understanding these categories is essential for proper asset allocation and risk management.</p>
    </section>

    <h2>How is Market Cap Calculated?</h2>
    <p>The formula for calculating market capitalization is remarkably simple:</p>
    <div class="card" style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: bold; padding: 2rem;">
      Market Cap = Current Stock Price × Total Outstanding Shares
    </div>
    <p><strong>Example:</strong> If a company has 50 million shares outstanding and its stock is currently trading at $100 per share, its market capitalization is $5 billion.</p>

    <h3>The "Share Price" Illusion</h3>
    <p>A common mistake novice investors make is confusing the stock price with the size or value of the company. A company with a $500 stock price is not necessarily "bigger" or "more expensive" than a company with a $50 stock price. The $50 stock might belong to a massive corporation with billions of outstanding shares, while the $500 stock might belong to a small company with very few shares.</p>
    <p>Market cap provides the true measure of a company's total value, ignoring arbitrary share counts resulting from stock splits or buybacks.</p>

    <h2>The Categories of Market Cap</h2>
    <p>The investment community typically divides companies into three main tiers based on their market cap. While the exact dollar thresholds can shift slightly over time as the overall market grows, the general classifications are:</p>

    <h3>Large-Cap Stocks ($10 Billion or More)</h3>
    <p>Large-cap companies are the established giants of the business world. They have proven track records, dominant market positions, and global operations. Think of household names like Apple, Microsoft, Amazon, and JPMorgan Chase.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Risk Profile:</strong> Generally the least volatile and lowest risk. They are well-capitalized to weather economic downturns.</li>
      <li><strong>Growth Potential:</strong> Slower growth. Because they are already massive, it is mathematically harder for them to double or triple in size quickly.</li>
      <li><strong>Income:</strong> Many large-cap companies pay consistent dividends, making them attractive for those seeking <a href="/what-is-dividend-yield">Dividend Yield</a>.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Mid-Cap Stocks ($2 Billion to $10 Billion)</h3>
    <p>Mid-cap companies are in the sweet spot of the corporate lifecycle. They are established enough to have proven business models and consistent revenue streams, but small enough to still have significant runway for rapid expansion.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Risk Profile:</strong> Moderate risk. They are more volatile than large-caps but offer more stability than small-caps.</li>
      <li><strong>Growth Potential:</strong> High. These companies are often expanding aggressively, entering new markets, or capturing market share from larger competitors. They are also frequent targets for acquisition by large-cap firms.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Small-Cap Stocks ($300 Million to $2 Billion)</h3>
    <p>Small-cap companies are typically younger, emerging businesses serving niche markets or developing disruptive new technologies. They often have high growth potential but come with significant risks.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Risk Profile:</strong> High risk and high volatility. Small-caps are highly sensitive to economic shifts, interest rate changes, and sector-specific downturns. They generally have less access to capital and fewer resources to survive a severe recession.</li>
      <li><strong>Growth Potential:</strong> Highest. A successful small-cap company can grow exponentially, offering the potential for massive returns if they eventually graduate to mid-cap or large-cap status.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="card">
      <p>Note: You may also encounter the terms <strong>Mega-Cap</strong> (companies over $200 billion) and <strong>Micro-Cap</strong> (companies between $50 million and $300 million).</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Why Market Cap Matters for Your Portfolio</h2>
    <p>Understanding market cap is crucial because different sizes of companies behave differently during various phases of the economic cycle. For instance, small-caps often outperform during the early stages of an economic recovery, while large-caps tend to provide a safe haven during a recession.</p>

    <p>By diversifying your portfolio across all three market cap tiers, you can balance the aggressive growth potential of small-caps with the stability and dividend income of large-caps. This strategy of deliberate allocation across asset classes and sizes is a key component of <a href="/what-is-rebalancing">Portfolio Rebalancing</a>.</p>

    <p>To dig deeper into evaluating whether a company—regardless of its market cap—is currently overvalued or undervalued, read our complete guide on the <a href="/what-is-pe-ratio">P/E Ratio</a>.</p>

    <div class="card FAQ">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>How do you calculate market cap?</summary>
        <p>Market cap is calculated by multiplying a company's current share price by its total number of outstanding shares.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is considered a large-cap stock?</summary>
        <p>Large-cap stocks generally have a market capitalization of $10 billion or more. Examples include Microsoft, Apple, and Johnson & Johnson.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why does market cap matter?</summary>
        <p>Market cap matters because it indicates the size and perceived value of a company. It helps investors assess risk, growth potential, and volatility, allowing them to balance their portfolios accordingly.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>

